<h1>For wildfire smoke, don&#8217;t reach for the air filter. Grab a mop.</h1>

<p><em>Plus: What may imperil Colorado&#8217;s abortion &#8220;reversal&#8221; law</em></p>

</mj-text><mj-image width="500px" src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/BED4F991-6F90-40B6-96DD-57FB54F36254.png?w=1000" /><mj-text>

<p>Good midday, Colorado climate and health fans. Baseball playoffs don&#8217;t start until 6 p.m., so you have plenty of time to absorb this week&#8217;s meaty newsletter full of ideas about <strong>household smoke,</strong> <strong>new cars </strong>and when practicing <strong>health care</strong> overlaps with practicing <strong>religion</strong>.</p>

<p>One thing that strikes me about the debate over electrifying Colorado&#8217;s enormous car fleet is what we are not debating:<strong> free trade</strong> and <strong>big government subsidies</strong>. Remember when Democrats championed international free trade deals and populists eventually produced a backlash over <strong>NAFTA</strong> and the<strong> World Trade Organization</strong>? Seems like a long time ago.</p>

<p>Because the discussion at Colorado&#8217;s <strong>Air Quality Control Commission</strong> this week isn&#8217;t whether to subsidize new electric vehicles for consumers and automakers. Or whether a government should be deeply involved in planning a big sector of the economy. The only question is how high and how deep. At the moment, American society has arrived at a decidedly non-free-trade pact: Government will require that automakers produce mostly electric vehicles for the next 10 years, and in exchange, each consumer purchase will be subsidized by <strong>$10,000 to $15,000</strong> in rebates and credits.</p>

<p>As you&#8217;ll see below, one of the few things the AQCC is likely to discuss is whether to make the requirement for EVs for sale at about 80% in 2032, or take it all the way to 100% by 2035.</p>

<p>Modern manufacturing reality appears to have set in, from Washington, D.C., to Denver. We&#8217;re competing with an electrifying world. <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/10/05/business/nio-china-electric-vehicles.html?partner=slack&amp;smid=sl-share">China is propping up one electric vehicle-maker</a> to the tune of $35,000 in subsidies per new car, according to The New York Times.</p>

<p>An economy largely commanded by government policy, like we assume China&#8217;s is, <a target="_blank"  href="https://source.benchmarkminerals.com/article/china-is-building-one-battery-gigafactory-a-week-the-us-one-every-four-months-simon-moores">can put up a new battery factory in a matter of months</a>. Meanwhile, local officials in the U.S. appear to be growing quite used to ribbon-cutting for new job-creating facilities paid for with 30% tax credits from the Inflation Reduction Act. How much difference is there between a government slapping together a battery factory, and another government controlling auto makers and buyers?</p>

<p>Not passing judgment, just observing. From electric bikes to Teslas to wind towers, this clean tech revolution is brought to you in large part by the government. Never hurts to be aware.</p>

<p>Now, on to the news.</p>

