<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">CLIMATE</h4>

<h2>Clean Cars 2 would extend and accelerate EV changeover on Colorado roads</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/AP21057700560706.jpg?w=800" /><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>A 2021 Chevrolet Bolt EV on display in Michigan. Opinion polls show that most Americans would consider an EV if it cost less and there were more charging stations along freeways, and if automakers offered a bigger variety of models. (AP Photo/Carlos Osorio)</em></span></p>

</mj-text>
<mj-table>
	<tr style="border:2px solid white;">
	<td style="padding: 6px;text-align:center;font-size:22px;background-color:#fcd232;font-weight:bold;" width="40%">82%</td><td style="font-size:14px;padding:12px;color:#000000;background-color:#DCEEF2;" width="60%">Portion of new cars for sale that would have to be electric by 2032 under a state proposal</td></tr>
</mj-table>
<mj-text>

<p>Whether to push the<strong> electric vehicle revolution</strong> in Colorado all the way to a mandatory share of 82% of new cars for sale by 2032 is the big question for October&#8217;s Air Quality Control Commission meeting this week.</p>

<p>Zero or ultra-low emissions vehicles now account for between <strong>15% </strong>and <strong>20%</strong> of new car sales in Colorado and is rising fast, according to dealer and state registration statistics. But the current state rules mandating a steadily rising percentage of new EV sales (the original &#8220;Clean Cars&#8221; adopted by Colorado) would expire in 2025 if the AQCC does not pass <strong>&#8220;Clean Cars 2&#8221;</strong> this week.</p>

<p>Clean Cars 2, modeled as usual on California legislation mandating EV sales, would kick in for model year 2027 in Colorado and ramp up the required percentage of EVs on new car lots through 2032. That tops out at <strong>82%</strong>.</p>

<p>Environmental advocates want Colorado to adopt the full California rules, which run through 2035 and require all new car sales that year to be electric or equivalently clean plug-in hybrid electric vehicles. The Colorado health department&#8217;s Air Pollution Control Division staff has recommended stopping instead at the 82% requirement in 2032.</p>

<p>Colorado clean energy officials have said that once a car market gets beyond 80% of any particular drive train, the full transition to electric is inevitable, and 2032 is a fair cutoff.</p>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/Screen-Shot-2023-10-18-at-8.33.00-AM.png?w=800" /><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>Colorado would largely emulate California's requirements that car dealers offer more and more electric vehicles for sale each year. The dispute is over how high to go, in what year. (California Air Resources Board)</em></span></p>

<p>An environmental coalition led by the <strong>Sierra Club </strong>fears that leaves automakers too much wiggle room, advocating for the full, 100% California plan in prehearing filings with the commission.</p>

<p>&#8220;Passenger vehicles are Colorado&#8217;s largest source of transportation air pollution,&#8221; the coalition said. &#8220;This rulemaking presents the commission with an opportunity to take the bold action required to achieve a zero-emission passenger vehicle fleet â€” an outcome that is necessary to meet the state&#8217;s long-term pollution reduction goals.&#8221;</p>

<p>Auto dealers and other business interests, as you might expect, make the opposite argument, saying even Colorado&#8217;s 2032 cutoff at 82% may prove unrealistic and raise costs for consumers who can&#8217;t find affordable cars of any kind.</p>

<p>&#8220;In short, the issue isn&#8217;t acceptance, it&#8217;s timing. California&#8217;s timetable may well prove unworkable,&#8221; the <strong>Colorado Automobile Dealers Association</strong> said in its filing before the hearing.</p>

<p>The dealers said there has been a lull in consumer interest in buying EVs, and an increase in inventory, while unpredictable government rebates are propping up the market.</p>

<p>&#8220;While dealers are dedicated to pushing forward their EV fleet and doing everything legally within their capacity to help the state meet this goal, there is rampant uncertainty that our manufacturers collectively can produce enough (zero-emission vehicles) for Colorado to get us there,&#8221; the association said.</p>

<p><strong>CoPIRG</strong>, a consumer issues nonprofit that frequently advocates for ozone reduction and the transition away from fossil fuels, took up in-between ground in its prehearing public statements.</p>

<p>&#8220;While the goal is to reach 100% zero-emission vehicles on our roads, adopting the Colorado Clean Cars rule through 2032 would be a huge win both for consumers and the climate in our state,&#8221; said CoPIRG&#8217;s public health advocate <strong>Alexandra Simon</strong>.</p>

<p>We&#8217;ll bring you the results of this week&#8217;s discussion at the AQCC â€” which rarely these days ends up defying the recommendations of state health staff â€” in next week&#8217;s newsletter.</p>

