<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">HEALTH</h4>

<h2>Why lawmakers&#8217; own words could imperil Colorado&#8217;s new abortion &#8220;reversal&#8221; law</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/AP16307763058347.jpg?w=800" /><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>In this file photo, a Federal Protective Service officer enters the Alfred A. Arraj Courthouse in downtown Denver on Nov. 2, 2016. (AP Photo/P. Solomon Banda)</em></span></p>

<blockquote class="wp-block-quote" style="width:90%;max-width:500px;border-left: 4px double #fcd232;padding: 0px 10px;padding: 0px 10px;margin-left:0;"><span style="font-size:1.2em;line-height:1.3em;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-weight:bold;">&#8220;Do I have to become a scientific arbiter to decide this case?&#8221;</span><br><br><span style="font-size:1em;"><em>â€” U.S. District Court Judge Daniel Domenico</em></span></blockquote>

<p>Tuesday&#8217;s hearing on a motion to block Colorado&#8217;s new law on abortion pill &#8220;reversal&#8221; looked set to become a battle over the science.</p>

<p>Medical experts for both the plaintiff, a Catholic health clinic based in Englewood that is claiming the law violates religious freedom, and the state filed 469 pages of declarations and exhibits outlining what is â€” and isn&#8217;t â€” known about the practice.</p>

<p>But, as the hearing unfolded, U.S. District Court Judge <strong>Daniel D. Domenico</strong> made clear he felt ill-equipped to pick whose scientific arguments were more valid. What&#8217;s more, he didn&#8217;t think it was the most important question to answer.</p>

<p>&#8220;Do I have to become a scientific arbiter to decide this case?&#8221; Domenico at one point asked Assistant Attorney General <strong>Brian Urankar</strong>, who was representing the state medical and nursing boards in defending the law. &#8220;What difference does it make to me?&#8221;</p>

<p>Instead, Domenico zeroed in on questions about whether the law discriminates against the religious beliefs of the anti-abortion medical providers who brought the lawsuit.</p>

<p>Is there reason to think that the law isn&#8217;t a generally applicable medical regulation but rather a rule directed specifically at the plaintiffs based on their religious beliefs? If so, then the state might face a more stringent standard of review called strict scrutiny to uphold the law. (You can read more about the debate over whether strict scrutiny is appropriate in this case<strong> </strong><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/10/18/colorado-abortion-reversal-lawsuit-domenico/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>in our story today at coloradosun.com</strong></a><strong>.</strong>)</p>

<p>This is exactly what the plaintiffs in the case want Domenico to find, especially since he flatly said Tuesday that they would win if he did. But they also faced a problem: Providing progesterone to a patient who has taken the abortion drug mifepristone â€” which is what abortion pill &#8220;reversal&#8221; is â€” is not an inherently religious act.</p>

<p>&#8220;There&#8217;s also other purposes why someone could engage in this,&#8221; Domenico said to <strong>Mark Rienzi</strong>, the the president and CEO of the <strong>Becket Fund for Religious Liberty</strong> and an attorney representing the plaintiffs in the case.</p>

<p>In other words, doctors could choose to provide the treatment without having a religious motive for doing so. Since the state argues that the ban on abortion pill reversal is about upholding medical standards and protecting patients from unscientific health care, why should Domenico consider this religious discrimination?</p>

<p>But here lawmakers&#8217; own words could come back to haunt them. Sponsors of the bill to ban abortion pill reversal specifically mentioned the religious affiliation of the clinics that provide it during legislative arguments over the bill.</p>

<p>Rienzi pointed to comments that Sen. <strong>Janice Marchman</strong>, a Loveland Democrat and one of the bill&#8217;s sponsors, made during a committee hearing this spring. Marchman said the bill was intended to regulate &#8220;anti-abortion centers.&#8221; She then continued:</p>

<p>&#8220;What is an anti-abortion center? They're also known as crisis pregnancy centers and fake clinics. They are faith-based organizations that pose as a comprehensive reproductive health care clinic to intercept patients seeking abortion care.&#8221;</p>

<p>At another point, Marchman referred to &#8220;religious-based pregnancy centers.&#8221; Other lawmakers made references during legislative debates to clinics that offer abortion pill reversal being faith-based or acting with religious motives.</p>

<p>All of this provides grist for the plaintiffs&#8217; argument that lawmakers knew the law would specifically target religious organizations. And that could make it harder for the law to withstand Domenico&#8217;s â€” or, later, <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/09/29/colorado-abortion-pill-reversal-law-lawsuit/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">potentially an appellate court&#8217;s</a> â€” review.</p>

<p>A ruling on the injunction request is expected later this week or early next. <strong>We&#8217;ll have a story up on coloradosun.com when it comes down.</strong></p>

