<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">MORE HEALTH NEWS</h4>

<ul><li><strong>Colorado is paying parents to take care of children with disabilities, a pandemic benefit that&#8217;s sticking around. </strong>&gt;&gt; Parents of children with disabilities often struggle to string together care options for their kids. But, during the pandemic, the federal government changed the rules to allow the parents, themselves, to get paid for providing the care. That was a godsend for many families, but it was set to end as federal pandemic support programs go away. Now, as <strong>Jennifer Brown</strong> reports, Colorado is continuing the program in a more limited way. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/10/17/medicaid-children-with-disabilities/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>The Colorado Sun</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>Colorado&#8217;s radon mitigation assistance program has become more popular. </strong>&gt;&gt; Colorado homes are at high risk for problems with radon, an odorless, colorless, tasteless gas that can cause cancer with repeated exposure. But radon-mitigation systems are expensive. Enter a state program to help people with low incomes afford the systems. And enter reporter <strong>Jennifer Oldham</strong> to explain how the state legislature has stepped up with more money for the increasingly popular program. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/10/13/colorado-radon-mitigation-assistance-program-popular/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>The Colorado Trust</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>&#8220;They are afraid to come to work.&#8221; Violence against health care workers is on the rise in Colorado. </strong>&gt;&gt; National and local surveys show an increase in attacks on health care workers â€” they&#8217;re being punched, kicked and spit on. It&#8217;s happening in hospitals and clinics across the state, and health care leaders say it is emerging as the most pressing workforce issue they face. &#8220;I usually have good instincts about patients, but not this time,&#8221; a behavioral health counselor who was attacked on the job told reporter <strong>Monte Whaley</strong>. &#8220;There is just this increase in aggressiveness from patients. They are not as predictable as they used to be.&#8221; &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/10/12/violence-against-colorado-health-care-workers/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>The Colorado Sun</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>A homeless recovery campus at an old fort on the plains is so successful Colorado is making more. </strong>&gt;&gt; Reporter <strong>Jennifer Brown</strong> last visited <strong>Fort Lyon</strong>, a former Army post in Las Animas that the state has converted into a place for people who are homeless to receive services and get back on their feet, in 2018. At the time, <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2018/09/11/fort-lyon-colorado-homeless-audit/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">data on its benefits was mixed</a>. This month, she went back and found a program now considered so successful that the state is looking to replicate it. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/10/16/homeless-recovery-campus-fort-lyon/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>The Colorado Sun</strong></a></li>
</ul>

