</mj-text><mj-text margin="0" padding="0"><h3 style="padding:.3em;font-family:'Libre Franklin','Arial Black';font-weight:700;background-color:#fcd232;font-size:24px;text-align:center;">CHART OF THE WEEK</h3></mj-text>
<mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/Screen-Shot-2023-10-17-at-9.00.37-PM.png?w=800" /><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>September set more records for the hottest 9th month in recorded weather history, even beating the average July for recent years. (NOAA)</em></span></p>

<p>Ahhh, September, the beginning of cool nights and leaf colors and a wardrobe change for <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.theonion.com/mr-autumn-man-walking-down-street-with-cup-of-coffee-1819574012">Mr. Autumn Man</a>. Right?</p>

<p>Not so much, lately. Hate to tell you that the recent string of &#8220;hottest months ever&#8221; continued in the ninth frame of 2023, with September&#8217;s world average even beating the average July from the early 2000s. If you&#8217;ve worried that global warming seems to have dragged September from the &#8220;fall&#8221; category squarely into &#8220;summer,&#8221; you&#8217;re increasingly correct, <a target="_blank"  href="https://public.wmo.int/en/media/news/september-smashes-monthly-temperature-record-record-margin#:~:text=September%20was%20far%20and%20away,by%20far%20the%20warmest%20September.">according to experts like the World Meteorological Organization</a>. The chart from NOAA, above, of world land temperature &#8220;anomalies&#8221; gives you a visceral red snapshot of where things got the hottest last month.</p>

</mj-text><mj-text margin="0" padding="0"><h3 style="padding:.3em;font-family:'Libre Franklin','Arial Black';font-weight:700;background-color:#fcd232;font-size:24px;text-align:center;">HEAT MAP<br /><span style="font-size:12px;text-transform:uppercase;font-weight:normal;"><em>Climate &amp; health news Coloradans need to help find their way</em></span></h3></mj-text><mj-text>

<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">CLIMATE</h4>

<ul><li><strong>Landlocked Colorado has a crack hurricane forecasting team. </strong>&gt;&gt; And some of the researchers fly straight into the worst storms, Tracy Ross reports. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/10/13/a-csu-grad-student-flew-into-a-hurricane/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>The Colorado Sun</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>Rusty crayfish, zebra mussels, tamarisk: Climate warming boosts invasive species in Colorado River Basin. </strong>&gt;&gt; We&#8217;ve reported some of these items, but is there a bigger picture threat that warming brings to invasive species stories? &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://thehill.com/policy/equilibrium-sustainability/4246099-a-warming-colorado-river-grapples-with-invasive-species/"><strong>The Hill</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>Oil companies could win big capturing the carbon they released on the world. </strong>&gt;&gt; It&#8217;s a big bone of contention among environmentalists, who don&#8217;t want Big Oil profiting off their own chaos. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://news.oilandgaswatch.org/post/oil-gas-companies-and-major-investors-placing-big-bets-on-federally-subsidized-carbon-capture-technology"><strong>Oil and Gas Watch</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>The link between global warming and malnutrition. </strong>&gt;&gt; Growing food and getting it to the right places grows harder as the planet heats up. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-environment/interactive/2023/yemen-extreme-heat-hunger-malnourishment/?itid=hp-top-table-main_p003_f004"><strong>The Washington Post</strong></a></li>
</ul>

<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">HEALTH</h4>

<ul><li><strong>Kaiser Permanente reached a labor deal. So what&#8217;s in it? </strong>&gt;&gt; Workers in Colorado would get pay increases of 21% over four years and a $23 an hour minimum wage by 2026. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/10/13/kaiser-union-agreement-colorado-workers/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>The Colorado Sun/AP</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>A southwestern Colorado fire district wants to open an urgent care clinic. </strong>&gt;&gt; During the pandemic, the <strong>Upper Pine River Fire Protection District</strong> in La Plata County took an innovative approach to public health <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.the-journal.com/articles/upper-pine-river-fire-in-bayfield-plans-to-open-covid-19-vaccination-clinic/">by opening a COVID vaccination clinic</a>. Now, they are asking voters for funds to build a new fire station that includes a health care clinic. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.durangoherald.com/articles/upper-pine-planning-dual-fire-station-and-urgent-care-clinic/"><strong>The Durango Herald</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>Another barrier to abortion access: Employer-sponsored health plans. </strong>&gt;&gt; Health insurance provided to workers by about a quarter of large employers either heavily restricts abortion coverage or doesn&#8217;t cover it at all. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://kffhealthnews.org/news/article/abortion-coverage-kff-employer-survey/"><strong>KFF Health News</strong></a></li>

<li><strong>Yet another explanation for long COVID. </strong>&gt;&gt; A new study suggests that lingering virus in the gut may be inhibiting serotonin production. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/10/16/health/long-covid-serotonin.html"><strong>The New York Times</strong></a><strong>ðŸ”‘</strong></li>
</ul>

